{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Anita W. Addison | image = | imagesize = | caption = | birthname = Anita Laraine Wharton Addison | birth_date = 1952 | birth_place = [[Greensboro, North Carolina]], United States | death_date = January 24, 2004 | death_place = New York City, New York, United States | othername = Anita Addison | occupation = [[Television director|Television]] and film director, television producer | years_active = 1976–2004 }}
'''Anita W. Addison''' (September 6, 1952 – January 24, 2004) was an American [[Television director|television]] and film director and producer.
==Biography== Born in [[Greensboro, North Carolina]], Addison began working as a journalist before embarking on a directing and producing career. In the late 1980s, she worked as a senior VP of drama development at [[Lorimar Productions|Lorimar]] before working as a producer at [[Warner Bros. Television]]. In 1989, she earned an [[Academy Award]] nomination for directing the short film ''Savannah''.<ref name="variety">{{cite web|url=http://www.variety.com/article/VR1117899112.html?categoryid=25&cs=1|title=Anita Addison: Network TV exec|date=2004-01-28|publisher=variety.com|accessdate=2008-12-09}}</ref>
From 1995 to 1998, Addison was VP of drama development at [[CBS]]. After leaving CBS, she worked on numerous television series including ''[[Family Law (TV series)|Family Law]]'' and ''[[EZ Streets]]'' with director and writer [[Paul Haggis]]. In 1999, she directed the television movie ''[[Deep in My Heart (1999 film)|Deep in My Heart]]''. Addison died on January 24, 2004 in New York City. Haggis dedicated his Oscar-winning film ''[[Crash (2004 film)|Crash]]'' to Addison.<ref name="variety" />
==Selected filmography==
===Director=== * ''Eva's Man'' (1976) * ''[[Freddy's Nightmares]]'' (1 episode, 1990) * ''[[Knots Landing]]'' (1 episode, 1991) * ''[[Sisters (U.S. TV series)|Sisters]]'' (1 episode, 1991) * ''There Are No Children Here'' (1993) * ''[[ER (TV series)|ER]]'' (1 episode, 1995) * ''[[EZ Streets]]'' (1 episode, 1997) * ''[[Judging Amy]]'' (1 episode, 2000)
===Producer=== * ''Sisters'' (7 episodes, 1991) * ''[[That's Life (2000 TV series)|That's Life]]'' (22 episodes, 2001–02) * ''Copshop'' (2004)
